{"title_page": "1894 Georgetown football team", "text_new": "{{short description|American college football season}}\n{{Infobox college sports team season\n| sport = football\n| team = Georgetown\n| image = \n| image_size = \n| conference = Independent\n| record = 4\u20135\n| head_coach = [[Bob Carmody (American football)|Bob Carmody]]\n| hc_year = 1st\n| off_scheme = \n| def_scheme = \n| captain = \n| stadium = Georgetown Field\n| next = [[1898 Georgetown Blue and Gray football team|1898]]\n}}\n{{1894 Southern college football independents records}}\nThe '''1894 Georgetown Hoyas football team''' represented the [[Georgetown University]] during the [[1894 college football season]].  Georgetown finished the season with a 4\u20135 record.  [[Bob Carmody (American football)|Bob Carmody]] served as player-coach.  They played home games at Georgetown Field.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hoyafootball.com/records/games-1890s.htm|publisher=Hoya Football Project|title=Game By Game: 1891-1900|accessdate=March 24, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hoyasaxa.com/sports/hist01.htm|publisher=Hoya Saxa|title=Georgetown Football History: Chapter 1, Football's Roots at Georgetown|accessdate=March 24, 2019}}</ref>  During the final game against Columbia AC, Shorty Bahen was seriously injured and left partially paralyzed.  He died from his injuries four months later.  Georgetown disbanded its football team for three years as a result.  When the team reformed in 1898, only collegiate opponents were permitted.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hoyafootball.com/features/bahen.htm|publisher=Hoya Football Project|title=Death From The Gridiron|accessdate=March 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Schedule==\n{{CFB schedule\n\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = October 10\n| time = \n| w/l = w\n| away = y\n| opponent = {{cfb link|year=1894|team=Gallaudet Bison|title=Gallaudet}}\n| stadium = Kendall Green\n| cityst = [[Washington, D.C.|Washington, DC]]\n| score = 16\u20130\n| attend = \n}}\n|{{CFB schedule 