{"title_page": "All My Loving", "text_new": "{{About|the Beatles song|other uses}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2014}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2010}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = All My Loving\n| cover      = Allmyloving1964.jpg\n| alt        =\n| caption    = Canadian picture sleeve\n| type       = song\n| artist     = [[the Beatles]]\n| released   = {{Start date|1963|11|22|df=y}}\n| recorded   = 30 July 1963\n| studio     = [[Abbey Road Studios|EMI]], London\n| genre      =\n* [[Rock music|Rock]]\n* [[pop music|pop]]{{sfn|Pollack|1991}}\n| length     = 2:04\n| label      = [[Parlophone]] (UK)\n| writer     = [[Lennon\u2013McCartney]]\n| producer   = [[George Martin]]\n| misc       = {{Audio sample\n | type        = song\n | file        = Beatles_all_my_loving.ogg\n }}\n}}\n\n\"'''All My Loving'''\" is a song by the English rock band [[the Beatles]], from their second UK album ''[[With the Beatles]]'' (1963). It was written by [[Paul McCartney]]{{sfn|Miles|1997|p=148}} (credited to [[Lennon\u2013McCartney]]), and produced by [[George Martin]]. Though not officially released as a single in the United Kingdom or the United States, the song drew considerable radio airplay, prompting [[EMI]] to issue it as the title track of [[All My Loving (EP)|an EP]].{{sfn|MacDonald|2005|p=94}} The song was released as a single in Canada, where it became a number one hit. The Canadian single was imported into the US in enough quantities to peak at number 45 on the US [[Billboard charts|''Billboard'']] [[Billboard Hot 100|Hot 100]] in April 1964.{{sfn|Castleman|Podrazik|1975|pp=25, 347}}{{sfn|Wallgren|1982|p=23}}\n\n==Composition==\nAccording to journalist [[Bill Harry]], McCartney thought of the lyrics whilst shaving: \"I wrote 'All My Loving' like a piece of poetry and then, I think, I put a song to it later\".{{sfn|Harry|2000|pp=25\u201326}} However, McCartney later told biographer [[Barry Miles]] that he wrote the lyrics while on a tour bus and after arriving at the venue he then wrote the music on a piano backstage.{{sfn|Miles|1997|p=148}} He also said \"It was the first song [where] I'd ever written the words first. I never wrote words first, it was always some kind of accompaniment. I've hardly ever done it since either.\"{{sfn|Miles|1997|p=148}}\n\nThe lyrics follow the \"letter song\" model as used on \"[[P.S. I Love You (The Beatles song)|P.S. I Love You]]\",{{sfn|MacDonald|2005|p=94}} the [[A-side and B-side|B-side]] of their first single. McCartney originally envisioned it as a [[country & western]] song, and [[George Harrison]] added a [[Nashville sound|Nashville]]-style guitar solo.{{sfn|Miles|1997|p=148}}{{sfn|MacDonald|2005|p=94}} [[John Lennon]]'s rhythm guitar playing uses quickly strummed triplets similar to \"[[Da Doo Ron Ron]]\" by [[The Crystals]], a song that was popular at the time,{{sfn|MacDonald|2005|p=94}} and McCartney plays a [[walking bass]] line.<ref name=\"Everett2001\">{{cite book|last=Everett|first=Walter|title=The Beatles as Musicians: The Quarry Men Through Rubber Soul|url=https://archive.org/details/beatlesasmusicia00ever|url-access=registration|accessdate=7 November 2013|year=2001|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-514105-4|page=[https://archive.org/details/beatlesasmusicia00ever/page/189 189]}}</ref>\n\nLennon expressed his esteem for the song in his 1980 ''Playboy'' interview, saying, \"[I]t's a damn good piece of work{{nbsp}}... But I play a pretty mean guitar in back.\"{{sfn|Sheff|2000|p=171}}\n\nIt has been hypothesized that the piece draws inspiration from the [[Dave Brubeck Quartet]]'s 1959 song \"Kathy's Waltz\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/features/when-it-comes-to-songwriting-theres-a-fine-line-between-inspiration-and-plagiarism-2021199.html|title=When it comes to songwriting, there's a fine line between inspiration and plagiarism|last=Leigh|first=Spencer|date=8 July 2010|newspaper=[[The Independent]]|accessdate=26 December 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Recording==\nThe Beatles recorded the song on 30 July 1963 in eleven takes with three overdubs. The master take was take fourteen overdubbed on take eleven.{{sfn|Lewisohn|1988|p=34}} It was remixed on 21 August ([[monaural|mono]]){{sfn|Lewisohn|1988|p=34}} and 29 October ([[stereophonic sound|stereo]]).{{sfn|Lewisohn|1988|p=37}}\n\nA slightly longer stereo edition of the song, featuring a [[Hi-hat (instrument)|hi-hat]] percussion introduction not found on the common stereo or mono mixes was released in Germany and the [[Netherlands]] in 1965 on a compilation album entitled ''Beatles' Greatest''.{{sfn|Schaffner|1977|p=203}} This version was later released in the UK, but only as part of ''[[The Beatles Box]]'' (1980). It also turned up on a European CD bootleg release of the US ''[[Rarities (1980 The Beatles album)|Rarities]]'' with other bonus tracks not included on the original LP.\n\n==Releases and performances==\n* \"All My Loving\" was originally released in the UK on 22 November 1963 on ''[[With the Beatles]]''.{{sfn|Lewisohn|1988|pp=200\u2013201}}\n* The first US release was on ''[[Meet the Beatles!]]'', released 20 January 1964.{{sfn|Lewisohn|1988|pp=200\u2013201}}\n* The song was the title track of the ''[[All My Loving (EP)|All My Loving]]'' EP released in the UK on 7 February 1964.{{sfn|Lewisohn|1988|pp=200\u2013201}}\n* The song was released on another EP, ''[[Four by The Beatles]]'' in the US, on 11 May 1964.\n\n\"All My Loving\" was the Beatles' opening number on their debut performance on ''[[The Ed Sullivan Show]]'' on 9 February 1964;{{sfn|Harry|2000|p=1043}} the recording was included on ''[[Anthology 1]]'' (1995).{{sfn|Lewisohn|1995|pp=32\u201333}} The group also performed \"All My Loving\" three times for BBC radio, once in 1963 and twice in 1964. The final version, which was recorded on 28 February 1964, was included on ''[[Live at the BBC (The Beatles album)|Live at the BBC]]''.\n\nThe song was used twice in films by the group\u2014it plays in the background at the end of the nightclub scene in ''[[A Hard Day's Night (film)|A Hard Day's Night]]'' (1964), though without the drum opening and the coda; while an instrumental version appears in the film ''[[Magical Mystery Tour (film)|Magical Mystery Tour]]'' (1967).\n\nAccording to Alan Weiss, a TV producer who happened to be there, \"All My Loving\" was playing on the sound system at [[Mount Sinai West|Roosevelt Hospital]] emergency room when Lennon was pronounced dead after being [[Murder of John Lennon|shot on 8 December 1980]].{{sfn|Mcleod|2005}}\n\n==Reviews==\n\"All My Loving\" has been praised by several critics. [[Ian MacDonald]] said, \"The innocence of early Sixties British pop is perfectly distilled in the eloquent simplicity of this number\" and described the song as helping McCartney be seen as more of an equal to Lennon.{{sfn|MacDonald|2005|p=94}} [[Richie Unterberger]] of [[AllMusic]] said it \"was arguably the best LP-only track the Beatles did before 1964\" and that if it had been released as a single in America it would have been a huge hit.{{sfn|Unterberger|2009}}\n\nThe guitar work for \"All My Loving\" has also been lauded by later critics. Harrison's concise solo has been described as reminiscent of [[Chet Atkins]],<ref name=Margotin>{{cite book |first1=Philippe |last1=Margotin |first2=Jean-Michel |last2=Guesdo |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KXKnAgAAQBAJ&lpg=PT110&dq=%22all%20my%20loving%22%20rhythm&pg=PT110#v=onepage&q=%22all%20my%20loving%22%20rhythm&f=false |title=All The Songs: The Story Behind Every Beatles Release |year=2014 |publisher=Running Press}}</ref> and Lennon's complex rhythm work (relying on the unusual use of constant triplets<ref>{{cite book |first=Desi |last=Serna |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7fN2BgAAQBAJ&lpg=SA5-PA3&dq=%22all%20my%20loving%22%20rhythm&pg=SA5-PA3#v=onepage&q=%22all%20my%20loving%22%20rhythm&f=false |title=Guitar Rhythm and Technique For Dummies}}</ref>) was referred to as \"the most recognizable feature\"<ref>{{cite book |first=Boman |last=Desai |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=B3ePYKCa9ocC&lpg=PA20&dq=%22all%20my%20loving%22%20rhythm&pg=PA20#v=onepage&q=%22all%20my%20loving%22%20rhythm&f=falseDancing |title=About Architecture: A Songwriter's Guide to the Lennon-McCartney Catalog}}</ref> of the song; Lennon himself later described his performance as \"a superb piece of guitar.\"<ref name=Margotin/>\n\n==Personnel==\nPersonnel per [[Ian MacDonald]]:{{sfn|MacDonald|2005|p=94}}\n* [[Paul McCartney]] \u2013 [[double tracking|double-tracked]] lead vocals, bass guitar, \n*[[George Harrison]] \u2013 backing and harmony vocals and lead guitar\n*[[John Lennon]] \u2013  harmony vocals and rhythm guitar\n* [[Ringo Starr]] \u2013 drums\n* [[George Martin]] \u2013 [[Record producer|producer]]\n* [[Norman Smith (record producer)|Norman Smith]] \u2013 [[Audio engineer|engineer]]\n\n==Charts==\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Chart (1963\u201364)\n!Peak<br />position\n|-\n|Canada\n|align=\"center\"|1\n|-\n|Australian [[Kent Music Report]]<ref>{{cite book | title=Australian Chart Book (1940\u20131969) | author=Kent, David | publisher=Australian Chart Book | location=Turramurra | year=2005 | isbn=0-646-44439-5}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|1\n|-\n|{{singlechart|Belgium (Flanders)|16|artist=The Beatles|song=All My Loving|accessdate=16 May 2016}}\n|-\n|{{singlechart|Dutch100|2|artist=The Beatles|song=All My Loving|accessdate=16 May 2016}}\n|-\n|New Zealand (''Lever Hit Parade'')<ref>[http://www.flavourofnz.co.nz/index.php?qpageID=search%20lever&qartistid=8#n_view_location Flavour of New Zealand, 30 April 1964]</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|6\n|-\n|{{singlechart|Norway|2|artist=The Beatles|song=All My Loving|accessdate=16 May 2016}}\n|-\n|Swedish [[Sverigetopplistan|Kv\u00e4llstoppen Chart]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Swedish Charts 1962\u2013March 1966/Kv\u00e4llstoppen \u2013 Listresultaten vecka f\u00f6r vecka > Mars 1964|url=http://www.hitsallertijden.nl/charts/swedish%20charts/SwedishCharts1962-march66.pdf|publisher=hitsallertijden.nl|language=Swedish|accessdate=27 June 2018}}</ref>\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|-\n|{{singlechart|Billboardhot100|45|artist=The Beatles|song=All My Loving|accessdate=16 May 2016}}\n|-\n|US [[Cashbox (magazine)|''Cash Box'' Top 100]]<ref>{{cite book| first=Frank| last=Hoffmann| year=1983| title=The Cash Box Singles Charts, 1950-1981| publisher=The Scarecrow Press, Inc| location=Metuchen, NJ & London| pages= 32\u201334}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|31\n|-\n|West German [[Media Control]] Singles Chart<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.offiziellecharts.de/charts|title=Offizielle Deutsche Charts|format=Enter \"Beatles\" in the search box|publisher=[[GfK Entertainment Charts]]|language=German|accessdate=16 May 2016}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|32\n|}\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=40em}}\n\n==References==\n{{Refbegin}}\n* {{cite web\n| work=Pop Archives\n| year=2009\n| title=All My Lovin' - Johnny Young\n| url=http://www.poparchives.com.au/feature.php?id=1469\n| accessdate=20 October 2009\n| ref={{SfnRef|Pop Archives|2009}}\n}}\n* {{cite web\n| last=Anderson\n| first=Rick\n| year=2009\n| title=Review of ''Classic Scotty''\n| work=[[Allmusic]]\n| url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=r652937|pure_url=yes}}\n| accessdate=20 October 2009\n| ref=harv\n}}\n* {{cite web\n| last=Bregman\n| first=Adam\n| year=2009\n| title=Review of '' Blow in the Wind''\n| work=[[AllMusic]]\n| url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=r524559|pure_url=yes}}\n| accessdate=20 October 2009\n| ref=harv\n}}\n* {{cite book\n| last=Castleman\n| first=Harry\n| year=1975\n| last2=Podrazik\n| first2=Walter J.\n| title=All Together Now: The First Complete Beatles Discography, 1961\u20131975\n| publisher=[[Ballantine Books]]\n| location=New York\n| ref=harv\n}}\n* {{cite web\n| last=Eder\n| first=Bruce\n| year=2009\n| title=Overview of The Trends\n| work=[[AllMusic]]\n| url={{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p384094|pure_url=yes}}\n| acces